	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Aeka</b><br /><i>Now hold on.  If you look around multiple boards I post on you will see I constantly and vehimately say "Warriors need help."  You will also constantly see "Do not nerf Knights."  I see Warrior woes as an issue of Warrior functionality.  Where do Knights even figure into the eqaution?  Warrior agro control, which effects their effectiveness as a tank, is in a state of disrepair reguardless if Knights even existed.<br />
<br />
There is this strange idea that if Knights get nerfed, exp groups will run back to Warriors with open arms.  That groups will simply "put up" with Warrior flaky agro control.  Everything I experienced says that many will simply not try.  The only thing nerfing Knights will accomplish is that groups will search for a new method of tanking with solid agro generation.  Whether that is making Rangers tank or using a Beastlord pet or just going without any melee, it will be done much to the dismay of nerf mongering Warriors.<br />
<br />
As far as I can tell, Warriors who scream for nerfs only want to make the low end Knights suffer.  Removing agro from spells will have a consequence for raids which I'm sure most do not consider.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>This is quite possibly the most coherent version of what I am trying to point out. /clap<br />
<br />
The thread has been pretty much focused on exp groups. Bringing raids into the equasion, no one disputes the warrior's superiority at MT because of defensive. But changing how stuns work in EXP groups definatly changes the nature of stuns in raids.<br />
<br />
Regarding the use of stuns on raids. To reduce the aggro of stuns on raids messes with the raid system. BECAUSE of the aggro on stuns, paladins really only stun on a raid if A) add tanking B) the mob is trying to gate C) They need to pull aggro off the clerics/casters NOW.<br />
<br />
Currently, if a paladin were to be stunning during a raid to interrupt DPS of the mob or casting, he would be a grease spot for stealling aggro off the main tank. This is the number one issue with turing a grinding paladin into a raid paladin, gettin him/her to put away the stuns. If the aggro component were removed from the stuns, we would be stunning with reckless abandon, potentially perma-locking the mob if enough paladins/clerics were stunning on a chain. That I believe (and I think it was stated earlier) is why the aggro componnent was created in the first place. (Clerics were perma-stunning mobs in Seb) A perma stunned mob, doesnt fight back.. wheres the need for a MT there? Talk about the warriors shooting themselves in the foot. The one area where they are undisputibly the kings (MT on big mobs) would be gone. On a raid, a paladin CAN steal aggro, but a good paladin knows that he has no business doing that, because without defensive, we are nothing more than some dps, and some spot heals.<br />
<br />
And there it is. Changing stun to be less aggro generating will make raids more unbalanced. Catch - 22. Again, I see the solution as leaving Knights alone, and giving the warriors a boost at what they are supposed to do best. Tanking.</p>
	
	
	
